english:
  title: Preface to Poems of the Hall of Leisured Joy
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    What is the origin of the names 'leisure' and 'busyness'? Does it not stem from calling those in office busy and those in retirement leisured? When the ancients said 'the minister of the king labors not by his own fault,' they spoke of busyness. When they said 'to serve not princes, but to honor one's own calling,' they spoke of leisure. The distinction arises merely from the different stations one occupies.

    The Grand Minister Yoon, Lord of Mauseong, constructed a separate hall as a retreat, inscribing its entrance 'The Hall of Leisured Joy.' Given his rise through learning and virtue to the rank of Chief Minister, his service to two reigns, his merit recorded in the state archives, his standing with the sovereign like an arm and leg, his trust from the nation like a pillar and stone—how could such a man, attending ceaselessly to governance and instruction, truly possess leisure?

    When a curious observer posed this question to an old sage, the sage visited the Minister and offered this explanation: "Your Excellency's busyness and leisure belong to the state, not to your own will. Your leisure lies in the cultivation of sincerity and rectitude of heart. When intention is true and heart is right, virtue flourishes daily and the spirit remains at ease—this is what the ancients called the constancy of the noble man. Is this not your leisure?"

    The Minister demurred: "How could I claim such? This is the work of sages and worthies."

    The sage continued: "Yet though your person bears the weight of high office, though all burdens converge upon you, still your hand moves with effortless grace. To others you appear forever busy, yet you conduct affairs with perfect ease. Is this not leisure made joyful?"

    "Such was accomplished by the great ministers Xiao and Cao of Han, by Yao and Song of Tang," the Minister replied humbly. "I dare not claim their stature."

    "Then perhaps," suggested the sage, "you disdain the grandeur of mansions, prefer to dwell where flowers bloom and books line shelves, retiring behind closed doors to burn incense in quiet meditation—thus expressing your contentment in solitude?"

    "Close," said the Minister, "yet not quite."

    The sage, growing more perplexed, then offered his own interpretation: "Riches and poverty naturally move the common heart to joy and sorrow, yet the noble man views them as phantoms, external accidents. Though he may dwell in the halls of power, adorned with honor's raiment, he finds no joy in these things—not from disdain of wealth, but from forgetting it. Though he may dwell by desolate shores, eating plain fare, he knows no sorrow—not from loving poverty, but from forgetting it.

    "Your Excellency now holds the highest station, his achievements recorded in bronze and jade, his household honored with banners and insignia. Yet your heart befriends wind and blossom, snow and moon. You dwell where buildings lean over azure streams, where plum blossoms warm the window and bamboo groves deepen in mist. You brew tea for visiting monks and discourse through the long evening, seemingly unaware of your boundless merit and ten-thousand measures of stipend. In truth, you have cast off the ornaments of fame to walk alone with the Way, transcending the ten thousand things.

    "What you have forgotten is wealth and poverty. What brings you joy is the spacious, still, and solitary path. How could your body's busyness mar the leisure of your spirit? Just as the ancients, dwelling in abundance, treated riches as a wart or excrescence, so you have learned to dwell in honor while dwelling beyond it. This is the rare achievement that preserves both fortune and reputation.

    "Recently another nobleman built a pavilion by the western lake, naming it 'Befriending Gulls,' seeking likewise to forget the snare of fortune. Both worthies, matched in achievement and virtue, have reached the same truth without consultation. They are as the Duke of Zhou and the Duke of Zhao were to their king—supports of the realm whose renown shall echo through the ages.

    "Only then shall I understand how shallow my words of praise truly are."
